import React from 'react';
import "./Testimony.css";
  class Testimonyitems extends React.Component {
    componentDidMount(){
        function Slider(slider) {
            if (!(slider instanceof Element)) {
              throw new Error('No slider passed in');
            }
            // create some variables for working iwth the slider
            let prev;
            let current;
            let next;
            // select the elements needed for the slider
            const slides = slider.querySelector('.slides');
            const prevButton = slider.querySelector('.goToPrev');
            const nextButton = slider.querySelector('.goToNext');

            function startSlider() {
              current = slider.querySelector('.current') || slides.firstElementChild;
              prev = current.previousElementSibling || slides.lastElementChild;
              next = current.nextElementSibling || slides.firstElementChild;
              console.log({ current, prev, next });
            }

            function applyClasses() {
              current.classList.add('current');
              prev.classList.add('prev');
              next.classList.add('next');
            }

            function move(direction) {
              // first strip all the classes off the current slides
              const classesToRemove = ['prev', 'current', 'next'];
              prev.classList.remove(...classesToRemove);
              current.classList.remove(...classesToRemove);
              next.classList.remove(...classesToRemove);
              if (direction === 'back') {
                // make an new array of the new values, and destructure them over and into the prev, current and next variables
                [prev, current, next] = [
                  // get the prev slide, if there is none, get the last slide from the entire slider for wrapping
                  prev.previousElementSibling || slides.lastElementChild,
                  prev,
                  current,
                ];
              } else {
                [prev, current, next] = [
                  current,
                  next,
                  // get the next slide, or if it's at the end, loop around and grab the first slide
                  next.nextElementSibling || slides.firstElementChild,
                ];
              }

              applyClasses();
            }

            // when this slider is created, run the start slider function
            startSlider();
            applyClasses();

            // Event listeners
            prevButton.addEventListener('click', () => move('back'));
            nextButton.addEventListener('click', move);
          }
            const mySlider = Slider(document.querySelector('.slider'));
            console.log(mySlider);
        }
    render() {
        return (
            <>
            <section id="testimonies" className="slider">

            <div className="controls text-center">
             <button className="goToPrev"> Prev</button>
             <button className="goToNext">Next </button>
            </div>


            <div className="container">
              <div className="slides">
              <div className="slide" id="adebayo-kolade">
                <img src="assets/img/testimonials/adebayo-kolade.jpeg" alt=""/>
                <h3>Dr. Adebayo Kolade</h3>
                <h4>Ibadan, Nigeria</h4>
                <p>
                  <br/>When I joined SCM on Thursday Jan 18 (or 25, not sure) 1990, I did not even know I was joining a fellowship. I was a rather smallish boy from downtown who arrived late to resume. There was no money, so I did not make any attempt to seek accommodation.
                  <br/>I carried a free X-Ray from home, but when I found out that I needed to pay at Jaja, I sneaked out and carried my X-Ray around. I saw that I was posted to Kuti Hall, so I went to Kuti and roamed around. I was the only student from my secondary school who got admission into UI, and I only vaguely heard that 1 of our seniors ever got admitted to UI, so I had nobody to look for.
                  <br/>But my father always taught us that if we ever travelled away from home, we should find a temporary father where we went. The wooden block fascinated me. One old looking 100 Level student took me in (Room 29). As I roamed around, I found another old looking fresher who took interest in me. At first sight, I concluded that this should be a good school father. So, instead of staying in my Room 29, I spent most of my first 2 days in Room 40.
                  <br/>So, on Thursday evening, my new father took his Bible and said, Lets go. I followed him. And I just continued following him like Mumu. The whole thing was strange that day; it was so un-Baptist!
                  <br/>And then, so many people were trying to shake my hand  kilode??!!! I still remember Bro Sola Ajibulu holding the mic that day. So I kept following my school father Sundays and Thursdays. One day, it was raining, and we hid under the Senate building.
                  <br/>He reminded me of a popular Yoruba song, and thus recommended that we should follow Jesus into the rain. He stepped forward, and I followed him. By the time we reached Chapel, we were drenched. I followed him so much that my Dad at home knew I had another dad in school called Tade Majaro.
                  </p>
              </div>

              <div className="slide" id="adedimeji-aderonke">
                <img src="assets/img/testimonials/adedimeji-aderonke.jpeg" alt=""/>
                <h3>Adedimeji Aderonke</h3>
                <h4>Connecticut, US</h4>
                <p>
                  While at GCI/QSI, the spiritu santus nature of some of my female Christian classmates used to put me off. They were never smiling, so I did not want anything to do with them. In June, just before my UI admission, I was cleaning my parents living room when I saw an old and worn book called the Lydia book of the Baptist. Flipping through to see if it was worth saving, I ended up reading the whole book, full of salvation message. I felt so broken and convinced. I read the sinners prayers and there gave my life to Christ. That was the beginning of my Christian Journey. I longed for more books like this that shows your dependency and sufficiency only in Christ. With the help of the Daily Bread and the Gideons Bible with the Anglican hymns, I tried to fill some of the vacuum. This hunger and thirst followed me to UI. The decision of which fellowship to settle down with  IVCU or SCM  was made easy because the spiritu santus were in IVCU. Also, my class schedule favored the Thursday fellowship. So I settled myself in SCM to meet some familiar faces and welcoming hands. Of course we were a smaller group, but you could almost physically touch LOVE. They lived and carried the love of God in their eyes, their voices and their choices. I resolved to love and shape my life like this. The likes of my Bros. Kolapo, Tenu Adeosun, Babatunde Okikiolu, Sis Bola Sofela were my classmates and and also in SCM. We were all pampered and loved by the older ones. The love was also very genuine and no ulterior motives. People would choose to visit me on their birthdays. And you better be prepared to encourage them with some scriptures. Bro Biodun Adeniyi in Transport spoilt me, and when Bruuche my cousin took over, you can imagine what the squad of him and Bro Kenny Akindemowo did for me & Idia Hall Sisters. Bro Dave Fadugba was like a bigger brother I never had. Bro Tosin Odunsi was one of those jimjim brothers you see like Father Christmas especially when he moved to UCH. Bro Charles with his tenses, grammar and accents was my president when I joined the fellowship and I think sis Toyin Adesokan was the Vice. Strong and dont mess with her Her bible study class will make you want to read the whole bible. Bro Moses, our bible study sec was an encyclopedia of various editions of the Bible. He was always in his characteristics short sleeve shirt. Bro Bro Motunrayo was my follow up brother and you better be paying attention when he visit because he is very soft spoken. Those visit ensures that whatever you had for quiet time be ruminated upon because you can easily fall back to them during any follow up visit. Bro Biodun Olojo, was one President that checked upon us whenever we are having joint practice with IVCU choir during Easter/Festive season. Bro Victor Ola Akande and Bro Ebenezer babatope, I remember we decided to join grass root politics out when souls were perishing, it was simply joblessness. School was on strike but we learnt some core political moves. I remember I will write to encourage the new fellowship president during their swearing in. That always makes me pray for them too. I recall my days with chapel Sunday school held in the basement and on Palm Sunday we will have the best behave students ride the donkey to around Abadina with the rest of the students walking behind with their palm leaves sing Hossanah . The chapel days reminds me of the ushers most of them were SCMers in the ushers robe and the likes of sis Nike and sister Iyeseun, in chapel choir as well as the pride I used to have with bro Niran Obasa at the piano, scm served with pride through bro Lekan Orenuga, sis Funmi Olukoju, sis Bola  Olusesi, my sis Omolade Adebayo. SCMers were very active in chapel. and friends like Bro Olumide Folalu, Bro Mike Ogundimbola, Bro Olumide Ajibawo, were as close as a glove. Free and relaxed with SCMers, I never needed to act in SCM. Choir was such a closely knit family, and we were special. The EDV with Bros Kenny Olatoye, Ayoola Aladeojebi, Niran Obasa  Im going to get myself into trouble now because everyone in Choir was special to me. Oh! I cant forget Sis Oyoma; classmate, choir and same hall. Sis Evelyn roommate  more than a sister. My All the Rere ma ni o popular choir song team. I remember I used to ride with Sister Iyabo Obasanjo in her Volkswagen Beetle back to the hall before I joined the exco. I remember how we shared everything. All exco had to accommodate as many sisters as your roommate will allow. As the former treasurer, the new treasurer had no accommodation so, sis Motunde has to be with me. Unfortunately my sister too got admission and no accommodation. Making 3 of us, then bro Lekan Orenuga came for a 2mins visit and brought a jambito from Ilu oke with him and as he was leaving he said sister Ronke, take care of her o. I ran after him what do you mean my roommate has her squatters and we are 3 already and it was a small D block in Queens hall. He stepped back and said, if she were to be a brother I wont come here. Im entrusting her into your care. When my sister came back to see that I have another person to share my corner with, she called my Daddy that she needs her own accommodation promptly because there was no end to how many people I will keep accommodating. But I bless God for that opportunity because my jambito of 1992 is a full professor today and assisted me in obtaining admissions for some of our kids on this platform. She is Prof.Simbo Apata nee Arowojolu.
                  <br/>I remember the Ilorin crusade where we were to go into the street to invite people. You have to consciously relegate your poise and sarcadelicness and speak in undiluted Yoruba language to the indigenes. Preached to them, led them to Christ and invited them for the crusade which was starting a few hours later that Friday. By the second day the news of the program had circulated well, courtesy those who attended the first day event. That was my first experience leading someone to Christ and I had two that day.<br/>I recall my experience on one of our trips to Ilorin when the bus landed in the bush and poison ivy dealt with us seriously. Another incident of poise in the garbage. What can you do when werepe starts dealing with you?! I remember I was affected the most.<br/>My story will not be complete if I dont mention that on these trips, starting from the moment we left Chapel, I mean immediately after prayers, Bro Lawal would give me no peace. There had to be something I said or did not say. My school of thought had to be error-laden. We would argue from beginning till we got to our destination. I remember clearly one day the President Bro Debo had to warn us that he would stop the bus and send us back to UI if we didnt stop. That got me thinking and I resolved not to assuage his argumentative poise. I promised to deal with him one on one, but he was very kind and brotherly when not in a crowd. Countless visits during those long breaks to each others houses.
                  <br/>I also recall the trip to Sis Joy & Bro Sam Okafors wedding. To begin with, Miracle (our bus) in her bid to demonstrate her name developed some drama, so we got to the event late and a lot was dependent on Hallelujah Choir because Bro Sam was our Papa. (He took care of us, visiting us like we were his biological children  thats another story for another time; the Balewa experience with Bro Sam Okafor, Bro Obiora Ikeobi and Bro Frank Asieba). Anyway, we ministered during the reception at Onitsha. All Yoruba boys and girls singing Igbo songs lai wo we (off heart), your guess is as good as mine! Trust Bro Oby who was conducting the ministration (loving as anything but dont mess with him when duty calls, and unfortunately he is a perfectionist); he had to tell me and a few others Me cho nu, meaning shut up. Sis Bukky Olojede was leading that song since majority of us had been me cho nued. So you kept dancing but you dared not sing those nonsense vocabularies that were making people laugh at us. Im sure you wonder what songs those were.<br/>Ta bu bochi, Jehovah meworo-2ce
                  <br/>Nunia nonu nimeya<br/>Ti hallelujah nimeya<br/>Ta bu bochi, Jehovah meworo.<br/>The wordings are something like that.<br/>Thank God Papa Sam is forgiving and he enjoyed his special day. Since that day, I resolved to practice any song ministration well. Can you imagine us singing Igbo songs in Onitsha and messing it up? Ridiculous!!!<br/>I think my resolution then started earning results as I started taking solos and giving special numbers. And I recall one I took with my dear friend, My Tribute which made me take personal likeness in Andrea Crouch of blessed memory. Guest what? Guess who? I took duet with your Uncle Lawal o. It was beautiful, we learnt each others verses just in case one forgets his or her lines. It was no competition rather it was the wealth of message. Effortless and soulful. How shall I say thanks for the things that youve done for me.<br/>Things so undeserved yet You gave<br/>To prove Your love for me<br/>The voices of a million angels<br/>Could not express my gratitude
                  <br/>All that I am, and ever hope to be<br/>I owe it all to Thee<br/>I recall my political experiment in UI. Right in my 200L, I was the Faculty VP. I really didnt receive support from brethren which I guess was for the fear of backsliding and knowing this I vouched that I would come out successfully; that brethren would even come for the Faculty dinner because it was going to be so comfortable to brethren (as in, no alcoholic drinks would be served, etc.). Well, I was a voice during my tenure, ensuring accountability and I recall an event when we went to offices/factories in Lagos, particularly Nigerian Breweries offered us Star & Gulder Larger beer, and I said we wanted just cash support or the softer drinks like Maltina as we were respectable University students. Guess what, the Marketing Manager practically walked me out. At the end of the day, I discovered that my exco team discovered why I wasnt successful with some of my assignments except with Coca-Cola. They went behind me and apologized and got their promise of beer load for the FASSA night. I couldnt even attend my FASSA week dinner talkless of inviting brethren. Why I share this is because of the important lesson I learned that a VP does not hold much power until the President is unavailable. With this realization and the need to secure accommodation for brethren I went for Idia Hall chairperson. When other brethren from other fellowships saw and supported my candidacy, my 3 opponents stepped down. So I became the only candidate for Chairperson. Unfortunately, on the eve of elections, I saw my results and they were not so encouraging. So I decided to not go again on the day of manifesto. Election came and I was voted for despite not showing up for the manifesto. I won but I did not take it up. In fact, I relocated to Queens Hall that year.
                  <br/>I recall those early morning evangelism trips for the drama, Escape. YouI can hear bro Okikiolus voice shouting Escape on those loud speakers as early as 5am. And this reminds me of Sis Enitan of blessed memory. Those were not any ordinary drama. SCM received a lift spiritually and numerically due to this event. And Im glad the culture is now an SCM tradition. Kudos to all drama group members of that year. That event made us to be more spiritually ready and vigilant.
                  <br/>I recall our exco meeting that some people claim I made them wait till after midnight in Chapel. For what? I wonder! When grammatical grenades are thrown about incessantly!! In one statement Bro Debo would have coined three new words softly spoken and juxtaposed, leaving half of us in wonderment of what he meant.
                  <br/>I enjoyed love like no one else, SCM was home within a home for me. Another event I remember was the eve of my 21st birthday. I was just getting ready to go home, had been ill since morning and Sister Bola Olusesi asked me to come stay in her room and she would take me home in the evening. Suddenly I became nauseous and I vomited. Sister Bola asked me to go and clean my face first with water, and as I turned to do that she locked the door so that I didnt have access to the room and she cleansed the emesis. If she didnt I would have continued the act because I could not see it and not start another round. But Ive been eternally grateful to that little saint and big but humble Sister Bola that showed me that when you love someone, you can clean up after them. She did not mind my dirtying her room. She took care of me and took care of the job. Thank you Sis Bola, you may not know how much you mean to me but you mean the world to me.
                  <br/>I have to stop before I get myself into trouble because I have good history with almost everybody. Lets wrap it up with kudos to the likes of Sisters Iyabo Duduyemi, Foluke Awotoye, Lade Ayeni, etc., who taught me how to make moimoi elewe whenever we had Awareness. Those fellowships that we moved around one anothers house during those ASUU strikes; those lovely brethren visits I received at home  I cannot forget.
                  <br/>I recall when SCM National was 50 and I was to be one of the ushers for the WSCF delegates but unfortunately their flight was delayed so they came late. I kept asking that I had to go home but the venue we used did not have commercial rides and it was on outskirts of the town at that time, so I had to wait for the National President to take me and others after he must have attended to the arriving delegates from outside the country. By the time he was ready, I was crying because I knew you dont disobey my mum. You just dont come home in the dark. It was not the time of cell phones. She would have waited endlessly at the shop and gone home out of fear, about 10-11pm. The way I was so afraid made him not drop others whose houses were on the way but he rushed to drop me home. We got home and fearfully I approached our gate. The whole street was dark (no light) but the generator was on so I knew my mum had not slept. I shook the gate and when my mum answered she told me to go back to where I was coming from. I told her it was a fellowship program but all my explanations fell on deaf ears. Mr Adegbolagun then spoke up appealing to her and she was furious asking him if he had children and if his daughters come home at 10pm after leaving the house since 8am. She would not open the gate and everyone in the car asked me to follow them back but I stayed, and a while after they left, she came to open the gate. Since then, I havent seen my poor National President to apologize for the insult.<br/>I had the good, the bad and the ugly, in UI. What built resilience in me and prepared me like no other for the larger world was that I had extra years in UI, not one semester, not 2 semesters, not 3 semesters but 4 semesters because the class that I had problem with was a second semester class which I didnt know I had problems with until the end of my 3rd year. This experience rendered my graduating grade to a pass. This gave me the experience and platform for a conscious and independent spiritual growth. I had the proverbial Israelite journey in life and I was made stronger for it. Ran a postgraduate course in OSU, became a Chartered Accountant, became CISA certified and came back for a Masters program in UI in 2004 before leaving the country and finding greater fulfillment in the medical field.
                  <br/>I seriously did not want to settle down with anybody in SCM but the pull was too strong. . So yes, I settled with one quiet brother in the Choir. ??
                </p>
              </div>

              <div className="slide" id="dave-fdugba">
            <img src="assets/img/testimonials/lanipekun-lawal.jpeg" alt=""/>
            <h3>Pastor Lawal Lanipekun</h3>
            <h4>Lagos, Nigeria</h4>
            <p>  <strong>MY SCM STORY</strong>
                <br/>I used to be known and addresed as Lawal Lanipekun-Reeves until I got married an my wife and I took the decision to drop all our non-African names and now my names are Adojutelegan Majiya Lanipekun-Lawal.My first encounter with Christianity was  as a junior High school student in December 1979. The UPN government in the South-West then had introduced the free education programme and with it came the opportunity for me to own a free Bible. It was at the invitation of a crush, that I joined the SU Movement in the school.<br/>However, I was like the proverbial seed that fell on the rock. It got withered because there was no root hold for it. I went radically back to Islam, the religion into which I was born and raised.
                <br/>Whilst studying for my A Levels at the Federal School of Arts and Science, Ondo (FSASON), I re-committed my heart to Jesus Christ and by November of the same year I resumed as a freshman in Sociology Department of the University of Ibadan.
                <br/>My first time at the Chapel of the Resurrection was  November 1987. That day was the last Sunday of the joint fellowship between SCM and IVCU, as a result of the suspension of religious activities on the UI campus during Babangida era. This was in response to the counsel we were given to immediately join a Christian Fellowship preferably a CU/ Nifes immediately we resumed in our various higher institutions of learning.<br/>The Chapel that day was full and the fellowship beautiful, the worship in particular was wonderful.<br/>At the end of the service, the announcement was made for new members  to either join the  Wednesday or the Thursday Bible study group. I decided to join the Thursday group and needless to say that I was terribly disappointed when I did not see the Sunday crowd on Thursday and the music was one kind. However the fellowship was rich and people smiled genuinely. I sat besides a Sister who I later knew to be Yinka Ajomale. She prayed and worshipped as if she was listening to a different kind of music than what I was hearing.
                <br/>Bro Charles Adeyanju preached that night and I could still picture him in my mind in his greyish-blue blazer on black trousers, I really could not remember the topic of his message ,but I could still recall  a line from his teaching  I could wish that myself were accursed from Christ for my brethren  I later found that quote to be from Romans That was the impact of the message on me that night .
                <br/>On getting to my room in E60 Zik Hall(wooden), I expressed my disappointment with regards to the attendance to one of my Christian room mates who advised that I could check out the Wednesday group. Just before I could do that, I received a visitor in the person of Brother Chika Okoroafor with whom I was upfront with my disappointment and many other questions about the fellowship. He calmly advised that I made a repeat visit on Sunday evening and when I did, the hall was still scantily filled and the music still bad, but this time around I felt I should stop complaining and instead lend myself to service in whatever ways  I could. When the call was made for people to join the choir, I registered myself with Sister Bukky Dipeolu and that night several freshers like Kolapo Oluseye, Muyiwa Ajakaiye, Ayo Ogunremi, Victor Ola-Akande, Olumide Fatokun, Agnes Bayode, Nike Adesogan, Ronke Adebayo, Sola Ajiboso, Dayo Ogunleye and many more joined. KTO who became my closest friend,  was the unofficial assistant to Sister Bukky until he later served  as the substantive leader of the Halleluyah choir.<br/>One of the days Bro Chika came visiting again and this time with Bro Sola Ajibulu who was introduced to me as the Zik Hall rep. On my first day of fellowship in his 2nd floor C Block room, I was called on to be the Evangelism coordinator for the hall.
                <br/>Bible studies were rich and deep, Sister Iyabo Duduyemi whom we nicknamed My Radical Sister was my first teacher, her class was inclusive and lively. Bro Moses Olayemi as the Bible syudy secretary was a wonder with the scriptures. I looked forward to his rounding up, cladded in his short sleeve shirt and pencil trousers, most times with  sandals to match.
                <br/>I took my assignment as Zik Hall Evangelism coordinator seriously, and I intended to make a success of it. But this was cut short. One Thursday evening towards the end of first semester in my 100 levels. Bro Charles began to announce the names of the new Excos to take over from his team. I was excitedly clapping for my friends whose names were somehow desrvedly called. Tenu Adeosun(Prayer), Okikiolu Babatunde(Evangelism), Yemi Ogunrin(Tedder HR), Lekan Orenuga(Bello HR), Bolanle Olusesi, Funmi Olukoju, Allwell  Ibeagha, Biodun Adeniyi  Morgan Nwoko and some of the names earlier mentioned in the choir.  Bro Chika Okoroafor who was announced as our president was a year one Diploma student of Library studies in the Faculty of Education. It was in the midst of thede that I heard my name.There must be another Lawal Lanipekun-Reeves, I thought. When my name was announced the third time,  Bro Tenu nudged me and said  Brother, e dide meaning,  wouldnt you stand up, Brother ?<br/>I got up with my knees knocking at each other, and sweating all over. No one consulted with me, and nothing prepared me for the shock.
                <br/>Even though, the others were freshers like me, they had integrated so well. Majority of the science students had been involved with PSSF which Tenu Adeosun coordinated. Just Allwell,  Agnes, Biodun,  Morgan, Bro Chika and myself were in the Humanities. I believe this was the beginning of growth and stability journey of SCM, UI.<br/>It was a large Exco, and other people who served  in that team who were however not freshers include but not limited to  Brothers and Sisters  Biodun Olojo, Tope Agesin, Debo Saba, Susan Ahaemefule, Lade Ayeni, Seun Adesogan, Sola Ajibulu, Foluke (VP) and many more.<br/>My first assignment was in the Twin office of Librarian/Colprteur. Library, I understood but who or what is a Call Porter ?  I had never heard the word before, neither did I even know how to spell it . Eventually, I found out that a Colprteur is merchandiser of books and other materials. This ]department enhanced my growth and balanced view because apart from reading all the books in the library at the time, I had the responsibility to read materials that would be recommended for the pbrethren. In spite of the fact that the department operated without any budgetary provisions, we grew and at a time I had to  recriut Augustina Bubu,(Prof Onome Davies) to assist me.
                <br/>My first career job, was as a salesman and merchandiser with the Leventis group. SCM gave my first cognate career experience. My other line of business now is still merchandising.
                <br/>I later took over from Bro Sola Ajibulu and served a term as the Zik Hall Rep. It was there during this period that I met and developed solid friendship with Tope Dosumu. We were room mates with Deji and Tola Tade. The four of us are  pastors of  growing and thriving churches  today ,to the glory of God. SCM was my first seminary.<br/>My last assignment in SCM leadership was as the Publicity and Publication Unit leader.
                <br/>I was actually called out and prayed for as the Fellowship PRO. That was how my predecessors in office,  Bro Morgan and Bro Dave Fadugba operated. I saw the weight of the assignment on them,  and I thought we should rebrand to meet the current realities and challenges of publicizing SCM at that time. We divided the assignment into two Publicity and creative writing (Publication). I had a hot headed creative,  Gbolahan Saba as a protg. He would first fight me and everyone else before coming out with great outdoor concepts and designs. Kolade Adebayo used to call himself a  bush boy   yet spoke and wrote better English than any city man I know. I used to wonder, what he was doing in Vet medicine. Tokunbo Owoseje, Fadekemi Oyewusi, Bunmi Afolayan, Bibilola Fatoki, Busola Omole, Tope Obaweya, Toyin Falode, Jabez Akindipe were some of the great people who made job easy.
                <br/>My second career is in the Media and Marketing Communications. PPU sowed the seed of creativity into me, for which Im forever grateful.<br/>Everywhere I looked, I see the hand of God through SCM in my life. SCM introduced me to leadership. Our exco meetings in those days were very robust and boisterous, especially when Bro Debo spoke those his English which we didnt understand, and stubborn Deronke would  decide not to yield grounds and keep us at Chapel basement till 2:00am. Now, when church workers and ministers act ungovernable, I remember how I stressed my presidents, especially  Bros  Sola and Debo in particular.<br/>I learnt how to prayerfully plan programmes and raise money for projects.
                <br/>There were different flavors of leadership. For Bro Chika, every meeting was deliverance, Bro Biodun almost turned all of us to Anglican priests. When Bro Sola went to Deeper Life we went with him and all of us were saying,   in Jeeesus naaame  like Pastor Kumuyi. It was a potpourri of leadership grace and I am the better for it.
                <br/>Our conferences and
                <br/>mission trips to Enugu, Port-Harcourt, Benin, Ile-Ife, Jos, Ilorin etc were my first time in some of those places.<br/>I particularly enjoyed those fellowship time during holidays when only a few of us would meet and thereafter go visiting brethren in their homes. I was also visited.<br/>I remember our small parties ,love feasts a b day picnics .
                <br/>I didnt know how much of the word l had in me and the grace to teach it until I went for the youth service where I was made the Bible stud secretary.
                <br/>I learnt stage crafts through my membership of the Deliverance Theater group. I wrote the play that was staged when my sister and friend, Enitan Ayansoga passed on. Yinka Fasoba had passed on a year before and we were all sad.<br/>Of all my getting from SCM, however,  I didnt get a wife. Actually  some of my friends made serious efforts at teaching  me on how to recieve a sister, I guess I wasnt spiritual enough.<br/>Well, God gave me a wonderful woman for a wife. We got married at Chapel of the Ressurection in the presence of many of my SCM family. She got the  feel and now shes an  SCMer by conversion. Head or tail SCM won.
                <br/>This in a nutshell is my SCM STORY, if I have the opportunity,  I will do it again and again.
                <br/>O God Bless our Movement SCM !
                <br/>
              </p>
            </div>

            <div className="slide" id="yinka-oridupa">
            <img src="assets/img/testimonials/Oridupa.jpeg" alt=""/>
            <h3>Dr. Yinka Oridupa</h3>
            <h4>Ibadan, Nigeria</h4>
            <p>
            My SCM Story
              <br/>I was admitted to UI in 1997 to study Vet Medicine, so I had in mind to study hard and enjoy myself being my first time away from home.
              <br/>I come from a solid bible-believing background under the tutelage of an IVCU alumnus and most of my church folks were in IVCU. I decided to avoid IVCU but I wanted a well grounded fellowship, not some jamboree centre with delinquent teenagers. I hope I dont sound too serious because Im really not an outwardly serious person but I believe God is serious about us.
              <br/>A friend and I was strolling pass Chapel that Thursday night and I heard this beautiful worship (led by Mercy) which I couldnt resist. I came in and realized it was end of fellowship, so I just sneaked out again. I was back the following Thursday and was in Bro Kadiris bible study class which was so in-depth and then the following week Bro Kolade. Bro Kunle Kasumu was the Gen Sec I think and he was quite inspirational.
              <br/>My squeaking in and out continued for over a year, until one Thursday that Tomiwa caught me as I was about to sneak out as usual and invited me to join the choir. By the way, I am a worship leader and that was why I didnt want to go to IVCU. I was the music director of our youth church choir from home and I wanted to come to UI to read. I was trying to hide but I couldnt do it for too long. I joined Halleluyah choir and that was when the beauty of Gods gift made a way for me. I enjoyed all our Jabulanis, praise concerts, choir ministrations and even fellowship worship time.
              <br/>I remember Bro Pec (Peculiar) once told me he used to record any worship session I led for his personal worship time. SCM gave me a bigger avenue to touch heaven with my worship. I have literarily seen heaven open during worship before. Worship still remains an integral part of my life, I live to worship God and lead people to Gods presence. Serving in the exco as SEFLO is another part and this opened up the world of alumni to me. I had to relate with very old people and even people that met me in school and left because I was in UI for 6years.
              <br/>I remember asking them if they were sure God told them I was to be in the exco because I knew I would radicalize the norm. I didnt believe in those long exco meetings, calling Bro and Sista this and that but disrespectful, among other unduly sanctimonious norms. I remember a family meeting where I said if calling me Sister, then a 600L student and exco member, was going to hinder our friendship drop the sister and call me my name. I was more interested in having Godly and truthful friends. SCM has blessed me with friends, family and especially a Godly mentor and father, Prof Saba.
              <br/>This is my SCM story.
            </p>
         </div>

         <div className="slide" id="kuforiji-gbenga">
            <img src="assets/img/testimonials/kuforiji.jpeg" alt=""/>
            <h3>Dr. Kuforiji Gbenga</h3>
            <h4>Ibadan, Nigeria</h4>
            <p>
            My SCM Story
              <br/>I gained admission to UI to study Veterinary Medicine in the year 1990. I came from a church background which encouraged me to join a Bible believing fellowship as soon as I got to school.
              <br/>I stayed in Independence hall room A1 in my first year. I was invited to SCM one Thursday evening by Bro Soji Ademuyiwa who also was in 100L with me at the time. He was visiting his course mate who happened to be my landlord at the time. My landlord was already attached to a Fellowship: that was my first week in UI. I moved to campus a bit later than my mates. I recall being visited by Sis Tundun.
              <br/>In my 200L, I was appointed Mellamby Hall repwhen I took over from Bro Tunji Shobayo. It was a great time to grow spiritually walking and working with the brethren. We had many sessions of fasting and retreats at ICS in which there was no food, no water: only air. That was the slogan.
              <br/>I remember I was an SCM Usher most of my stay in UI. I served with many AGSs: Sis Toyin Omope, Sis Tope Obaweya, Sis Bola Morohundiya, Sis Adeola (now Obasa) cant recall any other. I was usually situated in the central isle of the chapel.
