         <div className="slide" id="temidayo-ogunleye">
            <h3>Temidayo Ogunleye Ajakaiye</h3>
            <h4>Ibadan, Nigeria</h4>
            <p>
              My SCM Story
              <br/>My SCM journey started in my final year at a girls secondary school when a young man who had a sibling in my class came from OAU to do his teaching practice. I had always thought that this classmate of mine, Dupe had something special about her but the glow around her brother (name forgotten) was palpable, it was Jesus. He started a fellowship and as a Baptist, it made sense, so I went along. Our Principal was concerned that this Jesus thing was an unnecessary distraction and banned the fellowship but the seed had been sown.
              <br/>I gave my life to Christ in my local church just before resuming for my A levels. On the first day, an acquaintance invited me to the school fellowship. It happened to be a SCM fellowship. There I met the beautiful Morenike Adetunji and we became God lovers. We went to every seminar, revival programme and yours truly gave her life to Christ on many occasions until understanding came.
              <br/>Our Teachers were SCM alumni and would always invite those who were already on Campus to our event during Uni breaks. I remember seeing @Dave Fadugba on one of those occasions.
              <br/>UI  1987/88 to 1991/92
              <br/>It was a natural thing for me to join SCMUI when I eventually
              <br/>secured an accommodation in Idia Hall common room. I was taken aback by the size of the fellowship compared to my sixth form, it was relatively tiny. It made no difference, I felt at home and joined hallelujah choir. My induction to screaming hallelujah at the top of my voice, I still do now.
              <br/>Lots of learning and shaking at this stage, I remember being completely shocked when I was asked to borrow a white shirt to complete my uniform, I had not been to boarding school or faced with this level of sharing. I refused to sing/minister. Lets just say that by the time the Holy Spirit finished with me, I could have a whole outfit that no one in my biological family would recognise  all acquired (Pun intended). Sis Korede Adeola who left UI for OAU did help my understanding too.<br/>I was a reserved person and particularly enjoyed my own company but brethren would not leave me alone.<br/>My life in Idia hall had a layout:<br/>@ Omolade Olowe/Bukola Olojede if I fancy a good time<br/>@ Funmi Ajibulu/Bola Sofela  good time annex B<br/>@ Aderonke Adedimeji for cold water<br/>@ Egin Foluke Okunyade was probably the only source of my peanuts and other snacks<br/>@Ogbuefi Evelyn if I fancy a genuine chat about Jesus and my supply of music ministration with or without request<br/>@Tundun for a never ending pot of concortion  that sis can perform some magic with a few cups of rice and sparse condiments- chilli pepper, de rica and maggi cubes.<br/>Life was beautiful in spite of some of the challenges that ensued  leadership issues, a few brethren resitting their exams and dealing with grief.<br/>I had to deal with grief, as far as I can remember, for the first time with the passing of Sis Enitan. I asked questions, pondered a lot and it strengthened my christian walk.<br/>I chose to stay in Queens hall in my final year (500L) for various reasons and so glad that I did. The vibe was different to Idia halls but the love for the Lord no less.<br/>Serving as a Cell leader, Bible study teacher, Idia hall rep and later as Vice President were all great opportunities to fellowship, observe and grow. They were all part of the foundation and the growing that is continuing.<br/>My diplomacy was wonderful, I remember telling a sister who went to see a secular show at Trenchard Hall that I was disappointed in her as firmly as you could imagine. There were many cringe-worthy moments as I look back but I learnt from them all. At SCM, I learnt to follow, I learnt to lead and I learnt to be friendly.<br/>So I continued to serve God  true true!  and our then President, Olumuyiwa Ajakaiye, that I served with as VP came to my room on the day I was finally leaving UI and declared his manifesto. We got married in 1995.<br/>SCM Alumna
              <br/>Bizzarely, I dont miss you because you are with me in my spirit at all times even before social media. We shared so much that many of you never fail to turn up in my thoughts then I briefly long for you. I am intrigued to observe through our comments on this platform, how much we share in common, how we have been shaped by our life encounters but what rings true for me is that Jesus Christ still takes the first place.
              <br/>This is the Revised Standard Version. Amplified Vesion available 1-2-1.
              <br/><strong>Temidayo Ogunleye Ajakaiye</strong>
              </p>
